son of Aonghus’.","Scottish: habitational name from the barony of Innes in Urquhart (Morayshire), named from Gaelic <i>inis</i> ‘island’.","English: variant of   Ince  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Inniss","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Innes  ."]},{"name":"Ince","meanings":["habitational name from Ince in Makerfield (Lancashire), Ince (Cheshire), or Ince Blundell (Lancashire). The placenames derive from Proto-Welsh <i>ïnïs</i> ‘island’.","possibly a post-medieval West Midlands variant of <b>Hints</b>, a habitational name from either of two places called Hints (Staffordshire, Shropshire). The placenames probably derive from Proto-Welsh <i>hïnt</i> ‘way, path’ + Middle English plural <i>-es</i>.","possibly a variant with plural or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i> of <i>Inn</i>, from residence at an <i>inn</i> or <i>inns</i>, from Middle English <i>in</i> (singular) or <i>innes</i> (plural) ‘tavern, lodging(s), tenement(s)’. There seems also to have been some confusion with Scottish   Innes  ."]},{"name":"Inch","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Innes  .","English: perhaps, at least in some cases, a variant of   Ince  .","English: variant of   Hinch  ."]},{"name":"McInnis","meanings":["Scottish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Aonghuis</b>, a patronymic from the personal name <i>Aonghus</i> (see   Angus  ). See also   McInnes  , compare Irish   McGinnis  ."]},{"name":"Innis","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Innes  .","English: variant of   Ince  ."]},{"name":"Inness","meanings":["Scottish (Durham and Northumberland): variant of   Innes  ."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["Formed from Margaret."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Margaret Innes was born about 1350, in Scotland, United Kingdom. She married Robert Maitland Laird of Gight in Scotland, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. She died after 1380, in her hometown."},"et":{"Abt 1350–deceased":"umbes 1350–pärast 1380","1330–1400":"1330–1400","1380–1440":"1380–1440","–Male":"Surnud","1350–1380":"1350–1380","Abt 1350":"umbes 1350","deceased":"pärast 1380","1400":"1400","1440":"1440","1330":"1330","1350":"1350","1380":"1380","Scotland, United Kingdom":"Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Gight, Fyvie, Aberdeenshire, Scotland":"Fyvie, Aberdeenshire, Scotland","Scotland":"Šotimaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"Abt 1350–deceased":"noin 1350–1380 jälkeen","1330–1400":"1330–1400","1380–1440":"1380–1440","–Male":"Kuollut","1350–1380":"1350–1380","Abt 1350":"noin 1350","deceased":"1380 jälkeen","1400":"1400","1440":"1440","1330":"1330","1350":"1350","1380":"1380","Scotland, United Kingdom":"Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Gight, Fyvie, Aberdeenshire, Scotland":"Fyvie, Aberdeenshire, Scotland","Scotland":"Skotlanti, 